servings: 2
time required: 30 minutes
cuisine: North America
course: main course
---

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat #oven{} to 400 degrees. Toss @cauliflower florets{10%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast in oven until tender and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Bring 1 cup water, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, and a pinch of salt to boil in a small #pot{}. Stir in @bulgur wheat{1/2%cup} and cover. Lower heat and reduce to a simmer. Cook until tender, ~{12-15%minutes}. Remove from heat and keep covered.

While bulgur and cauliflower cook, heat @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a small pan over medium heat. Stir in @chili flakes{1%tsp} (to taste—start with a pinch and add more if you like it spicy), @cumin{1%tsp}, and a pinch of salt and pepper. Cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Remove from heat and set aside.

Quarter @Persian cucumber{1} lengthwise, then chop into ½-inch-thick pieces. Pick @dill{1/4%ounce} fronds from stems and roughly chop. Zest and halve @lemon{1}. Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce} lengthwise.

Mix together @yogurt{1/2%cup}, ¼ cup diced cucumber, half the dill, and a squeeze of lemon in a small #bowl{}. Season with salt and pepper.

> We sent more yogurt for the tzatziki sauce.

Divide bulgur between plates. Top with tomatoes, remaining cucumber, and cauliflower. Dollop with tzatziki sauce. Garnish with @pepitas{1%ounce}, lemon zest, and remaining dill, then lightly drizzle with spiced oil.

> Think cauliflower is forever destined to be a side dish? Think again! Roasting the creamy white vegetable transforms it into the star of the meal.